
[1]scrub

   SCRUB, v.t. [This word is probably formed on rub, or its root, and
   perhaps scrape, L. scribo, may be from the same radix.]

   To rub hard, either with the hand or with a cloth or an instrument;
   usually, to rub hard with a brush, or with something coarse or rough,
   for the purpose of cleaning, scouring or making bright; as, to scrub a
   floor; to scrub a deck; to scrub vessels of brass or other metal.

      SCRUB, v.i. To be diligent and penurious; as, to scrub hard for a
                                   living.

                                  SCRUB, n.

   1. A mean fellow; one that labors hard and lives meanly.

   2. Something small and mean.

   No little scrub joint shall come on my board.

   3. A worn out brush.
